post_text:
On April 2, Governor Kemp signed an Executive Order requiring residents and visitors of the State of Georgia to “shelter-in-place,” effective April 3, 2020, at 6:00 p.m. through 11:59 p.m., April 13, 2020, in line with the state’s public health emergency order, to ensure uniformity across the state. Governor Kemp’s executive order supplants any local ordinances or orders related to COVID-19 that have been adopted since March 1, 2020, including implemented curfew hours, while the executive order remains in effect.

The Peach County Board of Commissioners will follow Governor Kemp's orders. Please visit

https://gov.georgia.gov/document/2020-proclamation/statewide-shelter-place-handout/download

to view the Statewide Executive Order for more information and federal guidance to determine "critical infrastructure" from the Department of Homeland Security's Cyber-security and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA).

post_text:
Message from Chairman Moseley,

Earlier today, with the advice of our EMA Director Jeff Doles and Sheriff Terry Deese, I decided to extend the Peach County Executive Order to go through April 30th, 2020. As most of you have heard, Governor Kemp will order a "shelter in place" tomorrow for the entire state. Peach County fully supports this action. I will now wait for details of the Governor's order before amending / extending ours to avoid any confusion. You have heard the medical experts. You are seeing the numbers. Please stay home and limit interaction as much as possible. There will be exceptions as always: work, delivery, grocery, pharmacy, etc. It is up to us. Do not use these guidelines as a tightrope. It is too dangerous. Don't do it. Our deputies, fireman, ambulance service and 911 need all the support we can deliver. Staying home will be that support YOU can give them. More info will be available tomorrow. Thanks and God Bless, Martin Moseley, Chairman, Peach County Board of Commissioners.

Peach County Schools
March 16 at 12:04 PM ·

PRESS RELEASE
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: March 16, 2020 (REVISED)
CONTACT: The Admin.

PEACH COUNTY, GA - Peach County Schools are open today; however, based on updates received regarding the COVID-19 (Coronavirus) this morning, Peach County Schools will close until further notice, effective tomorrow, Tuesday, March 17.

Students will receive instructional packets to take home today. In addition, instructional resources will be posted on the district and school websites beginning Tuesday, March 17 until further notice.

Meals for students ages 18 and under will be available for pick up only, beginning Tuesday, March 17 between 11:00 a.m. until 1:00 p.m. until further notice. The pick-up sites will be Byron Middle School and Peach County High School.

We are in uncharted territory and we realize that many in our community are uncertain about the times ahead regarding the COVID-19 (Coronavirus). Peach County Schools feels the antidote for the uncertainty is strong faith and strong community. Thank you for your continued support, care and concern for our children.

Attention Homebound Seniors and Physically and Mentally Disabled Citizens of Peach County:
Byron Fire Departments, Byron Police Dept, Fort Valley Fire Department, Peach County Fire Department and Peach County Sheriff’s Office are willing to go pick up emergency essentials (such as food) and supplies (such as medicine) for you while we are facing the COVID-19 pandemic. This is only for persons who are homebound and unable to go collect these items for themselves. Please contact us at the Peach County 911 on our administrative line at 478-822-9111 if you need assistance.

post_text:
Black History Month in Peach County

David B. Carter, Jr., made it possible for black parents to become more involved in the making of decisions that affect their children's education. He was the first black person appointed to the Peach County Board of Education.

Also, the first black person elected to the Peach County Board of Commissioners.

Mr. Carter selected the profession of brick masonry where he subsequently became the owner of Carter’s Construction Company. He purchased land, subdivided into lots then sold and built the houses which ultimately created the Willow Lake Subdivision in Fort Valley, Peach County, GA.

Mr. Carter was in the grocery business as the owner of Carter’s Foodtown which was located on State University Drive in Fort Valley.

post_text:
You can help improve the lives of individuals in Georgia with mental illnesses, substance use disorders, and intellectual/developmental disabilities simply by completing a brief, anonymous questionnaire.

To participate, simply click on the link below:
www.surveymonkey.com/r/GeorgiaNeeds

This questionnaire is part of a survey being conducted by the Regional Advisory Councils of the Georgia Department of Behavioral Health and Developmental Disabilities (DBHDD). Your anonymous responses will be used to identify and recommend community/area priorities for improving DBHDD disability services locally, regionally, and statewide.

All Georgia residents are invited to participate in this survey. Please invite your friends, family, and colleagues to share their opinions. Speaking out about unmet needs and/or quality of services will go a long way toward improving the lives of citizens with disabilities across Georgia.

This questionnaire is also available in Spanish. The link to the Spanish version is www.surveymonkey.com/r/spGeorgiaNeeds.
